ALAS for Rome, the Rome that is no more,

The dauntless soul, the ever-ready hand, The patriot beart, that held it sweet to pour

Its dearest life-blood for its native land,

The fire of high ambition, conquest-fann’d‚ The iron will that nought could turn away

From strictest duty, matchless to command, Matchless to suffer, matchless to obey,

The consuls, and their legions, and the band Of hoary-bearded Fathers, where are they? Gone all, and gone for ever. N ever more The long triumphal pomp shall slowly wend With snowy victims on the Saered ⁴Way,

With priceless spoils and captives as of yore,

Nor see on high the old Tarpeian blaze With glittering roof, all-golden, nor ascend

The steep of marble as in other days ε For all thy triumphs now, alas 1 are o'er
